    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-11-20T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-11-20T17:00:00-05:00" n="320"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d320">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.114 Bodo/8: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Norway</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Biddle</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-11-20T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 20, 1935—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>18. Department’s No. 17, November 18, 5 p.m.<note n="77" xml:id="d320fn77">Not
                        printed.</note> If you see no objection, request Consulate General to inform
                    Shipping Company Nordfart (Erling Sannes), Bodo, Norway, owners of vessel <hi
                        rend="italic">Bodo</hi>, that it is expected that <hi rend="italic"
                        >Bodo</hi> will load large quantity alcohol at Antwerp for discharge on high
                    seas into smuggling vessels; that W. A. Shaw, Managing Director of Shaw
                    Steamship Company, Limited, of Halifax, by whom <hi rend="italic">Bodo</hi> is
                    said to have been chartered, has for several years been connected with the
                    ownership or operation of vessels engaged in smuggling; that Shaw’s former
                    shipping agents in Antwerp are said to have requested from his representative
                    guarantee that cargo would be landed at destination, which was refused, and they
                    gave up agency; that by allowing vessel to be used in connection with smuggling
                    they are apparently violating Norwegian law of June 25, 1926. If pressed for
                    reasons for belief cargo will be smuggled state that during past few months four
                    other steamers chartered by Shaw have discharged cargoes on high seas into
                    smuggling vessels. Telegraph reply.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
